Of these the main division stands at the end of the citation, the subdivision next below it at the begin· ning, and the smallest subdivision in the middle. Thus the reference to the Digest just given appears in Gentili (I.ch.1.a)² in the form I. 19. ἓ. 3. de capt. From the index which is prefixed to the texts of Mommsen and Krueger de capt. can be identified as D. 49, 15 and we at once have the complete citation D. 49, 15, 19, 3. The part of a law which precedes the numbered paragraphs is re- ferred to as principium, and the last law under a title as lex ultima. Examples are seen in the Advocatio I.1.b where the citation is l. 5 princ. de capt. and in the Advocatio ΙΙ. xxv. l where the reference l. ult. de re jud. is to D. 42, 1, 64.
